And that’s part of the reason why the country’s abortion laws are so poorly implemented,” Huerta told The Independent, commenting on the recent campaign carried out in the country to raise awareness within the community of reproductive rights for women.

Until 2007, abortion was illegal in Equatorial Guinea. It was 2017 when President Teodoro Obiang changed the legal framework by revision sex education, only to permit expulsion of a non-viable baby and abortion in extreme cases.

The time frame allowed for women to have terminations clinics and hospitals was as short as three months.

In 2018, the only public hospital in the country, the Hospital Militar General Calvo, began offering abortions, even though it continued to pay for the outreach of an evangelical Christian group that webcams with the families in rural areas. Therefore, it’s not permitted to perform abortions after the fourth month, but if it’s performed, it’s considered a criminal act that may end in “with prison sentences until the primacy of a servant of the State “going from one year for causing interruption voluntarily”, up to four years if there are reasons “of vital relevance”.

Women access this type of services through clandestine abortions through taxis.
